[[File:BM 91036.jpg|thumb|Land grant to Enlil-bānī ''nišakku-''priest, actually part of a dedicatory cone]]

The '''Enlil-bānī land grant [[kudurru]]''' is an ancient [[Mesopotamian]] ''narû ša ḫaṣbi'', or clay stele, recording the confirmation of a beneficial grant of land by [[Kassites|Kassite]] king [[Kadashman-Enlil I|Kadašman-Enlil I]] (ca. 1374–1360 BC) or [[Kadashman-Enlil II|Kadašman-Enlil II]] (1263-1255 BC) to one of his officials. It is actually a [[clay nail|terra-cotta cone]], extant with a duplicate, the orientation of whose inscription, perpendicular to the direction of the cone, in two columns and with the top facing the point, indicates it was to be erected upright, (on its now eroded base), like other entitlement documents of the period. 

==The text==

Excavated by [[Hormuzd Rassam]] on behalf of the [[British Museum]] at Abu Habba, ancient [[Sippar]], accessioned in 1883 and given Museum references BM 91036 and BM 135743, the cones stand around 25&nbsp;cm in height and have both lost their bases. They commemorate the donation of a sixty <small>GUR</small> field in twenty-three preserved lines on two columns and are without evidence of any of the sculptured religious iconography usually associated with this type of monument.<ref>{{ cite book | title = The Babylonian Entitlement narûs (kudurrus): A study in their form and function | author = Kathryn E. Slanksi | publisher = ASOR | year = 2003 | pages = 183–190 }}</ref> 

The donor of the original grant is identified as [[Kurigalzu I]], son of [[Kadashman-harbe I|Kadašman-Ḫarbe I]]. The clay cone memorializes the confirmation of this land grant on Enlil-bānī’s son or descendant, possibly his immediate successor to the office of ''[[nišakku]]-''priest, Ninurta-nādin-aḫḫē, by Kadašman-Enlil I, the monarch under whom he attained this office, or alternatively a descendant under the later reign of Kadašman-Enlil II. Brinkman considered that there was no compelling reason for either choice.<ref>{{ cite book | title = Materials and Studies for Kassite History | author = J. A. Brinkman | publisher = Oriental Institute of the University of Chicago | year = 1976 | page = 136 }}</ref> These kings' names are written with the divine determinative: <sup>d</sup>''ka-daš-man'' <sup>d</sup>''en-líl'' and <sup>d</sup>''ku-ri-gal-zu'', not normally considered a characteristic of Kassite king-names prior to the reign of [[Kurigalzu II]] (ca. 1332–1308 BC) although the evidence is scanty. The inscription is important as it was the first to distinguish unambiguously that Kadašman-Ḫarbe and Kadašman-Enlil were two different people and that, although the [[Kassite deities|Kassite deity]] Ḫarbe was considered equivalent in their pantheon to [[Enlil]], as witnessed on a Kassite-Babylonian vocabulary or synonym list, he was inscribed quite differently.<ref>{{ cite book | title = Babylonian boundary-stones and memorial tablets in the British Museum | author = L. W. King | publisher = British Museum | year = 1912 | pages = 3–4 }}</ref>

An individual by the name of Enlil-bānī is known in the genealogy of several people, such as his grandson, Enlil-kidinnī, who would become the prominent ''[[šandabakku]]'' or governor of [[Nippur]], and a descendant, Ninurta-rēṣušu, who was also to enjoy the post of ''nišakku-''priest during the reign of [[Nazi-Maruttash|Nazi-Maruttaš]] (ca. 1307–1282 BC), where Enlil-bānī is identified as having been the ''rabânum'' of <small>KUR.TI</small>, or mayor of the town later known as [[Dur-Kurigalzu]]. If this identification is correct, it would favor a dating of the artifact to the reign of Kadašman-Enlil I.<ref name=sollberger>{{cite journal | title = Two Kassite Votive Inscriptions | author = Edmond Sollberger | journal = Journal of the American Oriental Society | volume = 88 | issue = 1 | date = Jan–Mar 1968 | jstor = 597914 | pages = 191–197 | doi=10.2307/597914}}</ref>

