'''[[Albania]]''' is the biggest a producer of '''[[hydroelectricity]]''' in the world by percentage (90% as of 2011) and by own production (100%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.instat.gov.al/graphics/doc/tabelat/Treguesit%20Ekonomik/Energjia/ENR2008xls/Bilanci%20Energji%20Elektrike.xls |title='&#39;The Institute of Statistics (INSTAT)'&#39; |date= |accessdate=2011-03-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724164059/http://www.instat.gov.al/graphics/doc/tabelat/Treguesit%20Ekonomik/Energjia/ENR2008xls/Bilanci%20Energji%20Elektrike.xls |archivedate=2011-07-24 |df= }}</ref> Albania aims to increase its production to 100%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neurope.eu/articles/106616.php |title=Albania aims to be first green energy nation |date=23 May 2011 |work=[[New Europe (newspaper)|New Europe]] }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Some of the projects underway include [[Skavica Hydro Power Plant|Skavica]], up to 350 [[Watt|MW]], [[Devoll Hydro Power Plant|Devoll]]i 400 MW, [[Aoös|Vjosa]] up to 400 MW, Kalivaci and Ashta 48 MW hydropower plants, [[Valbonë (river)|Valbona]] and [[Tropojë]], 40 MW.

